# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elasticity-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] The **bulk modulus** ( K or B or k ) of a substance is a measure of the resistance of a substance to bulk compression.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] It is defined as the ratio of the infinitesimal pressure increase to the resulting *relative* decrease of the volume.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Other moduli describe the material's response (strain) to other kinds of stress: the shear modulus describes the response to shear stress and Young's modulus describes the response to normal (lengthwise stretching) stress.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] For a fluid, only the bulk modulus is meaningful.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] For a complex anisotropic solid such as wood or paper, these three moduli do not contain enough information to describe its behaviour, and one must use the full generalized Hooke's law.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] The reciprocal of the bulk modulus at fixed temperature is called the isothermal compressibility.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] where P is pressure, V is the initial volume of the substance, and $dP/dV$ denotes the derivative of pressure with respect to volume.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] where $\rho$ is the initial density and $dP/d\rho$ denotes the derivative of pressure with respect to density.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] The inverse of the bulk modulus gives a substance's compressibility.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Generally, the bulk modulus is defined at constant temperature as the isothermal bulk modulus, but can also be defined at constant entropy as the adiabatic bulk modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Strictly speaking, the bulk modulus is a thermodynamic quantity, and in order to specify a bulk modulus it is necessary to specify how the pressure varies during compression: constant-temperature (isothermal $K_{T}$ ), constant-entropy (isentropic $K_{S}$ ), and other variations are possible.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Such distinctions are especially relevant for gases.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] where $\gamma$ is the heat capacity ratio.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] When the gas is not ideal, these equations give only an approximation of the bulk modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] In solids, $K_{S}$ and $K_{T}$ have very similar values.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Solids can also sustain transverse waves: for these materials one additional elastic modulus, for example the shear modulus, is needed to determine wave speeds.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] It is possible to measure the bulk modulus using powder diffraction under applied pressure or at elevated temperatures, as well as by other methods for fluids, elastomers, minerals such as olivines, using theoretical calculations, of even granular materials such as sand grains.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] A material with a bulk modulus of 35 GPa loses one percent of its volume when subjected to an external pressure of 0.35 GPa (~3500 bar) (assumed constant or weakly pressure dependent bulk modulus).
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Since linear elasticity is a direct result of interatomic interaction, it is related to the extension/compression of bonds.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] It can then be derived from the interatomic potential for crystalline materials.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] First, let us examine the potential energy of two interacting atoms.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Starting from very far points, they will feel an attraction towards each other.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] As they approach each other, their potential energy will decrease.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] On the other hand, when two atoms are very close to each other, their total energy will be very high due to repulsive interaction.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Together, these potentials guarantee an interatomic distance that achieves a minimal energy state.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] Where U is interatomic potential and r is the interatomic distance.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] This means the atoms are in equilibrium.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] To extend the two atoms approach into solid, consider a simple model, say, a 1-D array of one element with interatomic distance of r, and the equilibrium distance is *r*0.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] At equilibrium, the first derivative is 0, so the dominant term is the quadratic one.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] When displacement is small, the higher order terms should be omitted.
[src:elasticity-physics/bulk-modulus] This form can be easily extended to 3-D case, with volume per atom(Ω) in place of interatomic distance.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] An **elastic modulus** is a quantity that describes an object's or substance's resistance to being deformed elastically (i.e., non-permanently) when a stress is applied to it.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The elastic modulus of an object is defined as the slope of its stress–strain curve in the elastic deformation region; a stiffer material will have a higher elastic modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] where *stress* is the force causing the deformation divided by the area to which the force is applied and *strain* is the ratio of the change in some parameter caused by the deformation to the original value of the parameter.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Since strain is a dimensionless quantity, the units of $\delta$ will be the same as the units of stress.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Elastic constants are specific parameters that quantify the stiffness of a material in response to applied stresses and are fundamental in defining the elastic properties of materials.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] These constants form the elements of the stiffness matrix in tensor notation, which relates stress to strain through linear equations in anisotropic materials.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Commonly denoted as *Cijkl*, where *i*,*j*,*k*, and *l* are the coordinate directions, these constants are essential for understanding how materials deform under various loads.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Specifying how stress and strain are to be measured, including directions, allows for many types of elastic moduli to be defined.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The *shear modulus* or *modulus of rigidity* (*G* or $\mu \,$ Lamé second parameter) describes an object's tendency to shear (the deformation of shape at constant volume) when acted upon by opposing forces; it is defined as shear stress over shear strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The shear modulus is part of the derivation of viscosity.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The *bulk modulus* (*K*) describes volumetric elasticity, or the tendency of an object to deform in all directions when uniformly loaded in all directions; it is defined as volumetric stress over volumetric strain, and is the inverse of compressibility.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The bulk modulus is an extension of Young's modulus to three dimensions.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] *Flexural modulus* (*E*flex) describes the object's tendency to flex when acted upon by a moment.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Two other elastic moduli are Lamé's first parameter, *λ,* and P-wave modulus, *M*, as used in table of modulus comparisons given below references.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Homogeneous and isotropic (similar in all directions) materials (solids) have their (linear) elastic properties fully described by two elastic moduli, and one may choose any pair.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Given a pair of elastic moduli, all other elastic moduli can be calculated according to formulas in the table below at the end of page.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Fluids at rest are special in that they cannot support shear stress, meaning that the shear modulus is always zero.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] This also implies that Young's modulus for this group is always zero.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] When moving relative to a solid surface a fluid will experience shear stresses adjacent to the surface, giving rise to the phenomenon of viscosity.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] In some texts, the modulus of elasticity is referred to as the *elastic constant*, while the inverse quantity is referred to as *elastic modulus*.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Density functional theory (DFT) provides reliable methods for determining several forms of elastic moduli that characterise distinct features of a material's reaction to mechanical stresses.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Utilize DFT software such as VASP, Quantum ESPRESSO, or ABINIT.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Overall, conduct tests to ensure that results are independent of computational parameters such as the density of the k-point mesh, the plane-wave cutoff energy, and the size of the simulation cell.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Incremental uniaxial strain: Apply small, incremental strains to the crystal lattice along a particular axis.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] This strain is usually uniaxial, meaning it stretches or compresses the lattice in one direction while keeping other dimensions constant or periodic.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Calculate stresses: For each strained configuration, run a DFT calculation to compute the resulting stress tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Stress-strain curve: Plot the calculated stress versus the applied strain to create a stress-strain curve.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The slope of the initial, linear portion of this curve gives Young's modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Mathematically, Young's modulus *E* is calculated using the formula *E*=*σ*/*ϵ*, where *σ* is the stress and *ϵ* is the strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Shear strain application: Apply small increments of shear strain to the material.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Shear strains are typically off-diagonal components in the strain tensor, affecting the shape but not the volume of the crystal cell.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Stress calculation: For each configuration with applied shear strain, perform a DFT calculation to determine the resulting stress tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Shear stress vs. shear strain curve: Plot the calculated shear stress against the applied shear strain for each increment.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The slope of the stress-strain curve in its linear region provides the shear modulus, *G*=*τ*/*γ*, where *τ* is the shear stress and *γ* is the applied shear strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Volume changes: Incrementally change the volume of the crystal cell, either compressing or expanding it.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] This is typically done by uniformly scaling the lattice parameters.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Calculate pressure: For each altered volume, perform a DFT calculation to determine the pressure required to maintain that volume.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] DFT allows for the calculation of stress tensors which provide a direct measure of the internal pressure.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] Pressure-volume curve: Plot the applied pressure against the resulting volume change.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The bulk modulus can be calculated from the slope of this curve in the linear elastic region.
[src:elasticity-physics/elastic-modulus] The bulk modulus is defined as *K*=−*VdV*/*dP*, where *V* is the original volume, *dP* is the change in pressure, and *dV* is the change in volume.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] In continuum mechanics and materials science, **elasticity** is the ability of a body to resist a distorting influence and to return to its original size and shape when that influence or force is removed.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Solid objects will deform when adequate loads are applied to them; if the material is elastic, the object will return to its initial shape and size after removal.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] This is in contrast to *plasticity*, in which the object fails to do so and instead remains in its deformed state.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The physical reasons for elastic behavior can be quite different for different materials.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] In metals, the atomic lattice changes size and shape when forces are applied (energy is added to the system).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] When forces are removed, the lattice goes back to the original lower energy state.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] For rubbers and other polymers, elasticity is caused by the stretching of polymer chains when forces are applied.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Hooke's law states that the force required to deform elastic objects should be directly proportional to the distance of deformation, regardless of how large that distance becomes.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] This is known as *perfect elasticity*, in which a given object will return to its original shape no matter how strongly it is deformed.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] This is an ideal concept only; most materials which possess elasticity in practice remain purely elastic only up to very small deformations, after which plastic (permanent) deformation occurs.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] In engineering, the elasticity of a material is quantified by the elastic modulus such as the Young's modulus, bulk modulus or shear modulus which measure the amount of stress needed to achieve a unit of strain; a higher modulus indicates that the material is harder to deform.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The SI unit of this modulus is the pascal (Pa).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The material's *elastic limit* or yield strength is the maximum stress that can arise before the onset of plastic deformation.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] When an elastic material is deformed due to an external force, it experiences internal resistance to the deformation and restores it to its original state if the external force is no longer applied.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] There are various elastic moduli, such as Young's modulus, the shear modulus, and the bulk modulus, all of which are measures of the inherent elastic properties of a material as a resistance to deformation under an applied load.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The various moduli apply to different kinds of deformation.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] For instance, Young's modulus applies to extension/compression of a body, whereas the shear modulus applies to its shear.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Young's modulus and shear modulus are only for solids, whereas the bulk modulus is for solids, liquids, and gases.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The elasticity of materials is described by a stress–strain curve, which shows the relation between stress (the average restorative internal force per unit area) and strain (the relative deformation).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The curve is generally nonlinear, but it can (by use of a Taylor series) be approximated as linear for sufficiently small deformations (in which higher-order terms are negligible).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] For even higher stresses, materials exhibit plastic behavior, that is, they deform irreversibly and do not return to their original shape after stress is no longer applied.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Elasticity is not exhibited only by solids; non-Newtonian fluids, such as viscoelastic fluids, will also exhibit elasticity in certain conditions quantified by the Deborah number.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] In response to a small, rapidly applied and removed strain, these fluids may deform and then return to their original shape.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Under larger strains, or strains applied for longer periods of time, these fluids may start to flow like a viscous liquid.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Because the elasticity of a material is described in terms of a stress–strain relation, it is essential that the terms *stress* and *strain* be defined without ambiguity.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Typically, two types of relation are considered.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The first type deals with materials that are elastic only for small strains.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The second deals with materials that are not limited to small strains.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Clearly, the second type of relation is more general in the sense that it must include the first type as a special case.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] For small strains, the measure of stress that is used is the Cauchy stress while the measure of strain that is used is the infinitesimal strain tensor; the resulting (predicted) material behavior is termed linear elasticity, which (for isotropic media) is called the generalized Hooke's law.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Cauchy elastic materials and hypoelastic materials are models that extend Hooke's law to allow for the possibility of large rotations, large distortions, and intrinsic or induced anisotropy.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The SI unit for elasticity and the elastic modulus is the pascal (Pa).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] This unit is defined as force per unit area, generally a measurement of pressure, which in mechanics corresponds to stress.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The pascal and therefore elasticity have the dimension L−1⋅M⋅T−2.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] For most commonly used engineering materials, the elastic modulus is on the scale of gigapascals (GPa, 109 Pa).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] As noted above, for small deformations, most elastic materials such as springs exhibit linear elasticity and can be described by a linear relation between the stress and strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] This relationship is known as Hooke's law.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] A geometry-dependent version of the idea was first formulated by Robert Hooke in 1675 as a Latin anagram, "ceiiinosssttuv".
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] He published the answer in 1678: "*Ut tensio, sic vis*" meaning "*As the extension, so the force*", a linear relationship commonly referred to as Hooke's law.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] where *k* is a constant known as the *rate* or *spring constant*.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] where *E* is known as the Young's modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Although the general proportionality constant between stress and strain in three dimensions is a 4th-order tensor called stiffness, systems that exhibit symmetry, such as a one-dimensional rod, can often be reduced to applications of Hooke's law.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The elastic behavior of objects that undergo finite deformations has been described using a number of models, such as Cauchy elastic material models, Hypoelastic material models, and Hyperelastic material models.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The deformation gradient (***F***) is the primary deformation measure used in finite strain theory.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Even though the stress in a Cauchy-elastic material depends only on the state of deformation, the work done by stresses might depend on the path of deformation.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Therefore, Cauchy elasticity includes non-conservative "non-hyperelastic" models (in which work of deformation is path dependent) as well as conservative "hyperelastic material" models (for which stress can be derived from a scalar "elastic potential" function).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] There is a tensor-valued function G such that ${\dot {\boldsymbol {\sigma }}}=G({\boldsymbol {\sigma }},{\boldsymbol {L}})\,,$ in which ${\dot {\boldsymbol {\sigma }}}$ is the material rate of the Cauchy stress tensor, and ${\boldsymbol {L}}$ is the spatial velocity gradient tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] If this third criterion is adopted, it follows that a hypoelastic material might admit nonconservative adiabatic loading paths that start and end with the same deformation gradient but do *not* start and end at the same internal energy.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Note that the second criterion requires only that the function G *exists*.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Hyperelastic materials (also called Green elastic materials) are conservative models that are derived from a strain energy density function (*W*).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] This formulation takes the energy potential (*W*) as a function of the deformation gradient ( ${\boldsymbol {F}}$ ).
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Linear elasticity is used widely in the design and analysis of structures such as beams, plates and shells, and sandwich composites.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] This theory is also the basis of much of fracture mechanics.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Hyperelasticity is primarily used to determine the response of elastomer-based objects such as gaskets and of biological materials such as soft tissues and cell membranes.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] In a given isotropic solid, with known theoretical elasticity for the bulk material in terms of Young's modulus, the effective elasticity will be governed by porosity.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Generally a more porous material will exhibit lower stiffness.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] More specifically, the fraction of pores, their distribution at different sizes and the nature of the fluid with which they are filled give rise to different elastic behaviours in solids.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Microscopically, the stress–strain relationship of materials is in general governed by the Helmholtz free energy, a thermodynamic quantity.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] Molecules settle in the configuration which minimizes the free energy, subject to constraints derived from their structure, and, depending on whether the energy or the entropy term dominates the free energy, materials can broadly be classified as *energy-elastic* and *entropy-elastic*.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] As such, microscopic factors affecting the free energy, such as the equilibrium distance between molecules, can affect the elasticity of materials: for instance, in inorganic materials, as the equilibrium distance between molecules at 0 K increases, the bulk modulus decreases.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] The effect of temperature on elasticity is difficult to isolate, because there are numerous factors affecting it.
[src:elasticity-physics/elasticity-physics] For instance, the bulk modulus of a material is dependent on the form of its lattice, its behavior under expansion, as well as the vibrations of the molecules, all of which are dependent on temperature.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The law is named after 17th-century British physicist Robert Hooke.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] He first stated the law in 1676 as a Latin anagram.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] He published the solution of his anagram in 1678 as: *ut tensio, sic vis* ("as the extension, so the force" or "the extension is proportional to the force").
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Hooke states in the 1678 work that he was aware of the law since 1660.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] It is the fundamental principle behind the spring scale, the manometer, the galvanometer, and the balance wheel of the mechanical clock.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The equation holds in many situations where an elastic body is deformed.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] An elastic body or material for which this equation can be assumed is said to be linear-elastic or **Hookean**.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law is a first-order linear approximation to the real response of springs and other elastic bodies to applied forces.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] It fails once the forces exceed some limit, since no material can be compressed beyond a certain minimum size, or stretched beyond a maximum size, without some permanent deformation or change of state.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Many materials will noticeably deviate from Hooke's law well before those elastic limits are reached.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The modern theory of elasticity generalizes Hooke's law to say that the strain (deformation) of an elastic object or material is proportional to the stress applied to it.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] However, since general stresses and strains may have multiple independent components, the "proportionality factor" may no longer be just a single real number, but rather a linear map (a tensor) that can be represented by a matrix of real numbers.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] In this general form, Hooke's law makes it possible to deduce the relation between strain and stress for complex objects in terms of intrinsic properties of the materials they are made of.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] For example, one can deduce that a homogeneous rod with uniform cross section will behave like a simple spring when stretched, with a stiffness k directly proportional to its cross-section area and inversely proportional to its length.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Consider a simple helical spring that has one end attached to some fixed object, while the free end is being pulled by a force whose magnitude is Fs.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Suppose that the spring has reached a state of equilibrium, where its length is not changing anymore.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Let x be the amount by which the free end of the spring was displaced from its "relaxed" position (when it is not being stretched).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law states that $F_{s}=kx$ or, equivalently, $x={\frac {F_{s}}{k}}$ where k is a positive real number, characteristic of the spring.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] A spring with spaces between the coils can be compressed, and the same formula holds for compression, with Fs and x both negative in that case.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] According to this formula, the graph of the applied force Fs as a function of the displacement x will be a straight line passing through the origin, whose slope is k.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law for a spring is also stated under the convention that Fs is the restoring force exerted by the spring on whatever is pulling its free end.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] In that case, the equation becomes $F_{s}=-kx$ since the direction of the restoring force is opposite to that of the displacement.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The torsional analog of Hooke's law applies to torsional springs.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] It states that the torque (τ) required to rotate an object is directly proportional to the angular displacement (θ) from the equilibrium position.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] It describes the relationship between the torque applied to an object and the resulting angular deformation due to torsion.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Just as in the linear case, this law shows that the torque is proportional to the angular displacement, and the negative sign indicates that the torque acts in a direction opposite to the angular displacement, providing a restoring force to bring the system back to equilibrium.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Hooke's spring law usually applies to any elastic object, of arbitrary complexity, as long as both the deformation and the stress can be expressed by a single number that can be both positive and negative.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] For example, when a block of rubber attached to two parallel plates is deformed by shearing, rather than stretching or compression, the shearing force *Fs* and the sideways displacement of the plates x obey Hooke's law (for small enough deformations).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law also applies when a straight steel bar or concrete beam (like the one used in buildings), supported at both ends, is bent by a weight F placed at some intermediate point.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The displacement x in this case is the deviation of the beam, measured in the transversal direction, relative to its unloaded shape.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] In the case of a helical spring that is stretched or compressed along its axis, the applied (or restoring) force and the resulting elongation or compression have the same direction (which is the direction of said axis).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Therefore, if Fs and x are defined as vectors, Hooke's equation still holds and says that the force vector is the elongation vector multiplied by a fixed scalar.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Some elastic bodies will deform in one direction when subjected to a force with a different direction.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] One example is a horizontal wood beam with non-square rectangular cross section that is bent by a transverse load that is neither vertical nor horizontal.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] In such cases, the *magnitude* of the displacement x will be proportional to the magnitude of the force Fs, as long as the direction of the latter remains the same (and its value is not too large); so the scalar version of Hooke's law *Fs* = −*kx* will hold.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] However, the force and displacement *vectors* will not be scalar multiples of each other, since they have different directions.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Moreover, the ratio k between their magnitudes will depend on the direction of the vector Fs.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Yet, in such cases there is often a fixed linear relation between the force and deformation vectors, as long as they are small enough.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Such a function is called a (second-order) tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] With respect to an arbitrary Cartesian coordinate system, the force and displacement vectors can be represented by 3 × 1 matrices of real numbers.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Therefore, Hooke's law **F** = ***κ*X** can be said to hold also when **X** and **F** are vectors with variable directions, except that the stiffness of the object is a tensor **κ**, rather than a single real number k.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The stresses and strains of the material inside a continuous elastic material (such as a block of rubber, the wall of a boiler, or a steel bar) are connected by a linear relationship that is mathematically similar to Hooke's spring law, and is often referred to by that name.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] However, the strain state in a solid medium around some point cannot be described by a single vector.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The same parcel of material, no matter how small, can be compressed, stretched, and sheared at the same time, along different directions.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Likewise, the stresses in that parcel can be at once pushing, pulling, and shearing.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] In order to capture this complexity, the relevant state of the medium around a point must be represented by two-second-order tensors, the strain tensor **ε** (in lieu of the displacement **X**) and the stress tensor **σ** (replacing the restoring force **F**).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The analogue of Hooke's spring law for continuous media is then ${\boldsymbol {\sigma }}=\mathbf {c} {\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }},$ where **c** is a fourth-order tensor (that is, a linear map between second-order tensors) usually called the stiffness tensor or elasticity tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] One may also write it as ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}=\mathbf {s} {\boldsymbol {\sigma }},$ where the tensor **s**, called the compliance tensor, represents the inverse of said linear map.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Being a linear mapping between the nine numbers *σij* and the nine numbers *εkl*, the stiffness tensor **c** is represented by a matrix of 3 × 3 × 3 × 3 = 81 real numbers *cijkl*.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] All three tensors generally vary from point to point inside the medium, and may vary with time as well.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The strain tensor **ε** merely specifies the displacement of the medium particles in the neighborhood of the point, while the stress tensor **σ** specifies the forces that neighboring parcels of the medium are exerting on each other.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Therefore, they are independent of the composition and physical state of the material.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The stiffness tensor **c**, on the other hand, is a property of the material, and often depends on physical state variables such as temperature, pressure, and microstructure.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Due to the inherent symmetries of **σ**, **ε**, and **c**, only 21 elastic coefficients of the latter are independent.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] This number can be further reduced by the symmetry of the material: 9 for an orthorhombic crystal, 5 for an hexagonal structure, and 3 for a cubic symmetry.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] For isotropic media (which have the same physical properties in any direction), **c** can be reduced to only two independent numbers, the bulk modulus K and the shear modulus G, that quantify the material's resistance to changes in volume and to shearing deformations, respectively.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Since Hooke's law is a simple proportionality between two quantities, its formulas and consequences are mathematically similar to those of many other physical laws, such as those describing the motion of fluids, or the polarization of a dielectric by an electric field.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] In SI units, displacements are measured in meters (m), and forces in newtons (N or kg·m/s2).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Therefore, the spring constant k, and each element of the tensor **κ**, is measured in newtons per meter (N/m), or kilograms per second squared (kg/s2).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] For continuous media, each element of the stress tensor **σ** is a force divided by an area; it is therefore measured in units of pressure, namely pascals (Pa, or N/m2, or kg/(m·s2).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The elements of the strain tensor **ε** are dimensionless (displacements divided by distances).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Therefore, the entries of cijkl are also expressed in units of pressure.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Objects that quickly regain their original shape after being deformed by a force, with the molecules or atoms of their material returning to the initial state of stable equilibrium, often obey Hooke's law.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Hooke's law only holds for some materials under certain loading conditions.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Steel exhibits linear-elastic behavior in most engineering applications; Hooke's law is valid for it throughout its **elastic range** (i.e., for stresses below the yield strength).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] For some other materials, such as aluminium, Hooke's law is only valid for a portion of the elastic range.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] For these materials a proportional limit stress is defined, below which the errors associated with the linear approximation are negligible.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Rubber is generally regarded as a "non-Hookean" material because its elasticity is stress dependent and sensitive to temperature and loading rate.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Generalizations of Hooke's law for the case of large deformations is provided by models of neo-Hookean solids and Mooney–Rivlin solids.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] A rod of any elastic material may be viewed as a linear spring.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The rod has length L and cross-sectional area A.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The modulus of elasticity may often be considered constant.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The potential energy *U*el(*x*) stored in a spring is given by $U_{\mathrm {el} }(x)={\tfrac {1}{2}}kx^{2}$ which comes from adding up the energy it takes to incrementally compress the spring.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] That is, the integral of force over displacement.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Since the external force has the same general direction as the displacement, the potential energy of a spring is always non-negative.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] This potential *U*el can be visualized as a parabola on the Ux-plane such that *U*el(*x*) = ⁠1/2⁠*kx*2.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] As the spring is stretched in the positive x-direction, the potential energy increases parabolically (the same thing happens as the spring is compressed).
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Since the change in potential energy changes at a constant rate: ${\frac {d^{2}U_{\mathrm {el} }}{dx^{2}}}=k\,.$ Note that the change in the change in U is constant even when the displacement and acceleration are zero.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Just as the potential energy can be written as a quadratic form in the internal coordinates, so it can also be written in terms of generalized forces.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The resulting coefficients are termed compliance constants.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] A direct method exists for calculating the compliance constant for any internal coordinate of a molecule, without the need to do the normal mode analysis.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The suitability of relaxed force constants (inverse compliance constants) as covalent bond strength descriptors was demonstrated as early as 1980.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Recently, the suitability as non-covalent bond strength descriptors was demonstrated too.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] A mass m attached to the end of a spring is a classic example of a harmonic oscillator.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] By pulling slightly on the mass and then releasing it, the system will be set in sinusoidal oscillating motion about the equilibrium position.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Isotropic materials are characterized by properties which are independent of direction in space.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Physical equations involving isotropic materials must therefore be independent of the coordinate system chosen to represent them.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The strain tensor is a symmetric tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Since the trace of any tensor is independent of any coordinate system, the most complete coordinate-free decomposition of a symmetric tensor is to represent it as the sum of a constant tensor and a traceless symmetric tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] where **I** is the second-order identity tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The first term on the right is the constant tensor, also known as the **volumetric strain tensor**, and the second term is the traceless symmetric tensor, also known as the **deviatoric strain tensor** or shear tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Using the relationships between the elastic moduli, these equations may also be expressed in various other ways.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] This is the form in which the strain is expressed in terms of the stress tensor in engineering.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The three-dimensional form of Hooke's law can be derived using Poisson's ratio and the one-dimensional form of Hooke's law as follows.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Similar treatment of directions 2 and 3 gives the Hooke's law in three dimensions.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The symmetry of the Cauchy stress tensor (*σij* = *σji*) and the generalized Hooke's laws (*σij* = *cijklεkl*) implies that *cijkl* = *cjikl*.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Similarly, the symmetry of the infinitesimal strain tensor implies that *cijkl* = *cijlk*.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] These symmetries are called the **minor symmetries** of the stiffness tensor **c**.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] This reduces the number of elastic constants from 81 to 36.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] These are called the **major symmetries** of the stiffness tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] This reduces the number of elastic constants from 36 to 21.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The major and minor symmetries indicate that the stiffness tensor has only 21 independent components.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] It is often useful to express the anisotropic form of Hooke's law in matrix notation, also called Voigt notation.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] $c_{pqrs}=l_{pi}l_{qj}l_{rk}l_{sl}c_{ijkl}$ where lab are the components of an orthogonal rotation matrix [*L*].
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The same relation also holds for inversions.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Orthotropic materials have three orthogonal planes of symmetry.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] A transversely isotropic material is symmetric with respect to a rotation about an axis of symmetry.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] To grasp the degree of anisotropy of any class, a **universal elastic anisotropy index** (AU) was formulated.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] It replaces the Zener ratio, which is suited for cubic crystals.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Linear deformations of elastic materials can be approximated as adiabatic.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] Under these conditions and for quasistatic processes the first law of thermodynamics for a deformed body can be expressed as $\delta W=\delta U$ where δU is the increase in internal energy and δW is the work done by external forces.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The work can be split into two terms $\delta W=\delta W_{\mathrm {s} }+\delta W_{\mathrm {b} }$ where *δW*s is the work done by surface forces while *δW*b is the work done by body forces.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] The right-hand side constant requires four indices and is a fourth-rank quantity.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] We can also see that this quantity must be a tensor because it is a linear transformation that takes the strain tensor to the stress tensor.
[src:elasticity-physics/hooke-s-law] We can also show that the constant obeys the tensor transformation rules for fourth-rank tensors.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] In materials science and solid mechanics, **Poisson's ratio** (symbol: **ν** (nu)) is a measure of the **Poisson effect**, the deformation (expansion or contraction) of a material in directions perpendicular to the specific direction of loading.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The value of Poisson's ratio is the negative of the ratio of transverse strain to axial strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] For small values of these changes, ν is the amount of transversal elongation divided by the amount of axial compression.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Most materials have Poisson's ratio values ranging between 0.0 and 0.5.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] For soft materials, such as rubber, where the bulk modulus is much higher than the shear modulus, Poisson's ratio is near 0.5.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] For open-cell polymer foams, Poisson's ratio is near zero, since the cells tend to collapse in compression.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Many typical solids have Poisson's ratios in the range of 0.2 to 0.3.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The ratio is named after the French mathematician and physicist Siméon Poisson.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] and positive strain indicates extension and negative strain indicates contraction.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Poisson's ratio is a measure of the Poisson effect, the phenomenon in which a material tends to expand in directions perpendicular to the direction of compression.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Conversely, if the material is stretched rather than compressed, it usually tends to contract in the directions transverse to the direction of stretching.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] It is a common observation when a rubber band is stretched, it becomes noticeably thinner.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Again, the Poisson ratio will be the ratio of relative contraction to relative expansion and will have the same value as above.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] In certain rare cases, a material will actually shrink in the transverse direction when compressed (or expand when stretched), which will yield a negative value of the Poisson ratio.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The Poisson's ratio of a stable, isotropic, linear elastic material must be between −1.0 and +0.5 because of the requirement for Young's modulus, the shear modulus and bulk modulus to have positive values.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] A perfectly incompressible isotropic material deformed elastically at small strains would have a Poisson's ratio of exactly 0.5.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Most steels and rigid polymers when used within their design limits (before yield) exhibit values of about 0.3, increasing to 0.5 for post-yield deformation which occurs largely at constant volume.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Rubber has a Poisson ratio of nearly 0.5.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Cork's Poisson ratio is close to 0, showing very little lateral expansion when compressed.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Some materials, e.g. some polymer foams, origami folds, and certain cells can exhibit negative Poisson's ratio, and are referred to as auxetic materials.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] If these auxetic materials are stretched in one direction, they become thicker in the perpendicular direction.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] In contrast, some anisotropic materials, such as carbon nanotubes, zigzag-based folded sheet materials, and honeycomb auxetic metamaterials to name a few, can exhibit one or more Poisson's ratios above 0.5 in certain directions.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The relative change of volume ⁠Δ*V*/*V*⁠ of a cube due to the stretch of the material can now be calculated.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] where K is bulk modulus and E is Young's modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] For a linear isotropic material subjected only to compressive (i.e. normal) forces, the deformation of a material in the direction of one axis will produce a deformation of the material along the other axis in three dimensions.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Here ν is Poisson's ratio, E is Young's modulus, **n** is a unit vector directed along the direction of extension, **m** is a unit vector directed perpendicular to the direction of extension.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Poisson's ratio has a different number of special directions depending on the type of anisotropy.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Orthotropic materials have three mutually perpendicular planes of symmetry in their material properties.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] An example is wood, which is most stiff (and strong) along the grain, and less so in the other directions.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The Poisson ratio of an orthotropic material is different in each direction (x, y and z).
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] However, the symmetry of the stress and strain tensors implies that not all the six Poisson's ratios in the equation are independent.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] There are only nine independent material properties: three elastic moduli, three shear moduli, and three Poisson's ratios.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] From the above relations we can see that if *E**x* > *E**y* then *ν**xy* > *ν**yx*.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The larger ratio (in this case *ν**xy*) is called the **major Poisson ratio** while the smaller one (in this case *ν**yx*) is called the **minor Poisson ratio**.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] We can find similar relations between the other Poisson ratios.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Transversely isotropic materials have a plane of isotropy in which the elastic properties are isotropic.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Therefore, there are five independent elastic material properties, two of which are Poisson's ratios.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] For the assumed plane of symmetry, the larger of *ν**xy* and *ν**yx* is the major Poisson ratio.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The other major and minor Poisson ratios are equal.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Some materials, known as auxetic, display a negative Poisson's ratio.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] When subjected to positive strain in a longitudinal axis, the transverse strain in the material will actually be positive (i.e. it will increase the cross sectional area).
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] For these materials, it is usually due to uniquely oriented, hinged molecular bonds.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] In order for these bonds to stretch in the longitudinal direction, the hinges must 'open' in the transverse direction, effectively exhibiting a positive strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] This can also be done in a structured way and lead to new aspects in material design, such as for mechanical metamaterials.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Studies have shown that certain solid wood types display negative Poisson's ratio exclusively during a compression creep test.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Initially, the compression creep test shows positive Poisson's ratios, but gradually decreases until it reaches negative values.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Consequently, this also shows that Poisson's ratio for wood is time-dependent during constant loading, meaning that the strain in the axial and transverse direction do not increase in the same rate.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Media with engineered microstructure may exhibit negative Poisson's ratio.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] In a simple case auxeticity is obtained removing material and creating a periodic porous media.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Lattices can reach lower values of Poisson's ratio, which can be indefinitely close to the limiting value −1 in the isotropic case.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] More than three hundred crystalline materials have negative Poisson's ratio.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] For example, Li, Na, K, Cu, Rb, Ag, Fe, Ni, Co, Cs, Au, Be, Ca, Zn Sr, Sb, MoS2 and others.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] At finite strains, the relationship between the transverse and axial strains *ε*trans and *ε*axial is typically not well described by the Poisson ratio.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] In fact, the Poisson ratio is often considered a function of the applied strain in the large strain regime.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] In such instances, the Poisson ratio is replaced by the Poisson function, for which there are several competing definitions.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] One area in which Poisson's effect has a considerable influence is in pressurized pipe flow.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] When the air or liquid inside a pipe is highly pressurized it exerts a uniform force on the inside of the pipe, resulting in a hoop stress within the pipe material.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Due to Poisson's effect, this hoop stress will cause the pipe to increase in diameter and slightly decrease in length.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The decrease in length, in particular, can have a noticeable effect upon the pipe joints, as the effect will accumulate for each section of pipe joined in series.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] A restrained joint may be pulled apart or otherwise prone to failure.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Another area of application for Poisson's effect is in the realm of structural geology.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Rocks, like most materials, are subject to Poisson's effect while under stress.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] In a geological timescale, excessive erosion or sedimentation of Earth's crust can either create or remove large vertical stresses upon the underlying rock.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] This rock will expand or contract in the vertical direction as a direct result of the applied stress, and it will also deform in the horizontal direction as a result of Poisson's effect.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] This change in strain in the horizontal direction can affect or form joints and dormant stresses in the rock.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Although cork was historically chosen to seal wine bottles for other reasons (including its inert nature, impermeability, flexibility, sealing ability, and resilience), cork's Poisson's ratio of zero provides another advantage.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] As the cork is inserted into the bottle, the upper part which is not yet inserted does not expand in diameter as it is compressed axially.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] The force needed to insert a cork into a bottle arises only from the friction between the cork and the bottle due to the radial compression of the cork.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] If the stopper were made of rubber, for example, with a Poisson's ratio of about 0.5, there would be a relatively large additional force required to overcome the radial expansion of the upper part of the rubber stopper.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] Most car mechanics are aware that it is hard to pull a rubber hose (such as a coolant hose) off a metal pipe stub, as the tension of pulling causes the diameter of the hose to shrink, gripping the stub tightly.
[src:elasticity-physics/poisson-s-ratio] (This is the same effect as shown in a Chinese finger trap.) Hoses can more easily be pushed off stubs instead using a wide flat blade.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] The derived SI unit of shear modulus is the pascal (Pa), although it is usually expressed in gigapascals (GPa) or in thousand pounds per square inch (ksi).
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] Its dimensional form is M1L−1T−2, replacing *force* by *mass* times *acceleration*.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] The shear modulus is one of several quantities for measuring the stiffness of materials.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] The shear modulus is concerned with the deformation of a solid when it experiences a force perpendicular to one of its surfaces while its opposite face experiences an opposing force (such as friction).
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] In the case of an object shaped like a rectangular prism, it will deform into a parallelepiped.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] Anisotropic materials such as wood, paper and also essentially all single crystals exhibit differing material response to stress or strain when tested in different directions.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] In this case, one may need to use the full tensor-expression of the elastic constants, rather than a single scalar value.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] One possible definition of a fluid would be a material with zero shear modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] In homogeneous and isotropic solids, there are two kinds of waves, pressure waves and shear waves.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] The shear modulus of metals is usually observed to decrease with increasing temperature.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] At high pressures, the shear modulus also appears to increase with the applied pressure.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] Correlations between the melting temperature, vacancy formation energy, and the shear modulus have been observed in many metals.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] Several models exist that attempt to predict the shear modulus of metals (and possibly that of alloys).
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] 2. the Steinberg–Cochran–Guinan (SCG) shear modulus model developed by M.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] Steinberg and used in conjunction with the Steinberg-Cochran-Guinan-Lund (SCGL) flow stress model.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] 3. the Nadal–Le Poac (NP) shear modulus model by Marie-Hélène Nadal and Philippe Le Poac that uses Lindemann theory to determine the temperature dependence and the SCG model for pressure dependence of the shear modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] where $\mu _{0}$ is the shear modulus at $T=0K$ , and D and $T_{0}$ are material constants.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] where, μ0 is the shear modulus at the reference state (*T* = 300 K, *p* = 0, η = 1), *p* is the pressure, and *T* is the temperature.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] The Nadal–Le Poac (NP) shear modulus model is a modified version of the SCG model.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] The empirical temperature dependence of the shear modulus in the SCG model is replaced with an equation based on Lindemann melting theory.
[src:elasticity-physics/shear-modulus] and μ0 is the shear modulus at absolute zero and ambient pressure, ζ is an area, *m* is the atomic mass, and *f* is the Lindemann constant.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Although Young's modulus is named after the 19th-century British scientist Thomas Young, the concept was developed in 1727 by Leonhard Euler.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] The first experiments that used the concept of Young's modulus in its modern form were performed by the Italian scientist Giordano Riccati in 1782, pre-dating Young's work by 25 years.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] The term modulus is derived from the Latin root term *modus*, which means *measure*.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] A solid material undergoes elastic deformation when a small load is applied to it in compression or extension.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Elastic deformation is reversible, meaning that the material returns to its original shape after the load is removed.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] At near-zero stress and strain, the stress–strain curve is linear, and the relationship between stress and strain is described by Hooke's law that states stress is proportional to strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] The coefficient of proportionality is Young's modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] The higher the modulus, the more stress is needed to create the same amount of strain; an idealized rigid body would have an infinite Young's modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Conversely, a very soft material (such as a fluid) would deform without force, and would have zero Young's modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus enables the calculation of the change in the dimension of a bar made of an isotropic elastic material under tensile or compressive loads.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] For instance, it predicts how much a material sample extends under tension or shortens under compression.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] The Young's modulus directly applies to cases of uniaxial stress; that is, tensile or compressive stress in one direction and no stress in the other directions.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus is also used in order to predict the deflection that will occur in a statically determinate beam when a load is applied at a point in between the beam's supports.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Other elastic calculations usually require the use of one additional elastic property, such as the shear modulus G , bulk modulus K , and Poisson's ratio $\nu$ .
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Any two of these parameters are sufficient to fully describe elasticity in an isotropic material.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] For example, calculating physical properties of cancerous skin tissue, has been measured and found to be a Poisson's ratio of 0.43±0.12 and an average Young's modulus of 52 KPa.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Defining the elastic properties of skin may become the first step in turning elasticity into a clinical tool.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus represents the factor of proportionality in Hooke's law, which relates the stress and the strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] However, Hooke's law is only valid under the assumption of an *elastic* and *linear* response.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Any real material will eventually fail and break when stretched over a very large distance or with a very large force; however, all solid materials exhibit nearly Hookean behavior for small enough strains or stresses.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] If the range over which Hooke's law is valid is large enough compared to the typical stress that one expects to apply to the material, the material is said to be linear.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Otherwise (if the typical stress one would apply is outside the linear range), the material is said to be non-linear.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Steel, carbon fiber and glass among others are usually considered linear materials, while other materials such as rubber and soils are non-linear.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] However, this is not an absolute classification: if very small stresses or strains are applied to a non-linear material, the response will be linear, but if very high stress or strain is applied to a linear material, the linear theory will not be enough.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] For example, as the linear theory implies reversibility, it would be absurd to use the linear theory to describe the failure of a steel bridge under a high load; although steel is a linear material for most applications, it is not in such a case of catastrophic failure.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] In solid mechanics, the slope of the stress–strain curve at any point is called the tangent modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] It can be experimentally determined from the slope of a stress–strain curve created during tensile tests conducted on a sample of the material.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus is not always the same in all orientations of a material.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Most metals and ceramics, along with many other materials, are isotropic, and their mechanical properties are the same in all orientations.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] However, metals and ceramics can be treated with certain impurities, and metals can be mechanically worked to make their grain structures directional.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] These materials then become anisotropic, and Young's modulus will change depending on the direction of the force vector.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Anisotropy can be seen in many composites as well.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] For example, carbon fiber has a much higher Young's modulus (is much stiffer) when force is loaded parallel to the fibers (along the grain).
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Other such materials include wood and reinforced concrete.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Engineers can use this directional phenomenon to their advantage in creating structures.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] The Young's modulus of metals varies with the temperature and can be realized through the change in the interatomic bonding of the atoms, and hence its change is found to be dependent on the change in the work function of the metal.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Additionally, the Rahemi–Li model links the temperature dependence of Young’s modulus in metals to changes in the electron work function, providing a theoretical basis using a generalized Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus of a material can be used to calculate the force it exerts under specific strain.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] where F is the force exerted by the material when contracted or stretched by $\Delta L$ .
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Note that the elasticity of coiled springs comes from shear modulus, not Young's modulus.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] When a spring is stretched, its wire's length doesn't change, but its shape does.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] This is why only the shear modulus of elasticity is involved in the stretching of a spring.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] or, in simple notation, for a linear elastic material: ${\textstyle u_{e}(\varepsilon )=\int {E\,\varepsilon }\,d\varepsilon ={\frac {1}{2}}E{\varepsilon }^{2}}$ , since the strain is defined ${\textstyle \varepsilon \equiv {\frac {\Delta L}{L_{0}}}}$ .
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] Young's modulus can vary somewhat due to differences in sample composition and test method.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] The rate of deformation has the greatest impact on the data collected, especially in polymers.
[src:elasticity-physics/young-s-modulus] The values here are approximate and only meant for relative comparison.
